{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600556/1930111601/0139.xml":{"full_text":"4\nFACTORS INDICATING\nBUSINESS RESUMPTION\nMan in Street Fails to See Conditions\nAre in Better Shape Than in\n1929, Says Writer.\n(Continued From Pi rut Page.)\nehtoery\u2014minus the balance wheel\u2014has\nslowed things down. We Insist on\nwearing blue-colored spectacles and\nmoping around Jlke sick pups, while our\nprincipal occupation is chewing rings\naround the edge of dimes as we debate\nWhether or not to let go of them.\nAlso, we persist in Jabbing the Wall\nStreet thermometer down the mouth of\nthe general business patient in order\nto see whether he is sick or well\u2014when\nas a matter of fact this thermometer\nIs broken, and always has been of\ndoubtful value.\nPeople scan the stock quotation pages\nof the daily newspapers, note the minus\nSigns, draw down the comers of their\nmouths, register first-class funeral ex\npressions and whine about bad business.\nNow, the stock market does not, never\nhas and never will discount actual busi\nness conditions. All it can do is to dis\ncount the public's knowledge of con\nditions. or discount the opinions of\nthose who express their convictions on\nthe ticker tape through buying or sell\ning.\nIt formerly was contended that the\nstock market discounted conditions\nfrom three to nine months ahead.\nWhat it really did was to discount the\npublic\u2019s knowledge of affairs. Now the\nvast amount of business statistics\npromptly made public has changed\nthings radically and last year the mar\nket not only did not discount condi\ntions. but even failed to reflect them\npromptly, and trailed hopelessly behind.\nBusiness turned down very definitely\naround the middle of the year, yet the\nstock market continued merrily on Its\nway upward until early In September\nand did not have much of a decline\nuntil October.\nTicker Tape BUnds Public.\nThe public must lift Its eyes from the\nWall Street game, with its present\ndoleful succession of \"snake eyes\u201d and\n\u2022\u2022little Joes\u201d to the rosy-hued dawn of\nthe approaching period of prosperous\nnormalcy\u2014not a period of hectic activ\nity and dangerous inflation, but a time\nof busy, happy prosperity. It must\nturn from the quotation page to view\nthe many promising indications and\noptimistic facts plainly apparent to\nthose who look for them. No wonder\nthe public can't see the signs of ap\nproaching real business and financial\nhealth when It has ticker tape across\nboth eyes.\nTo be sure, we are in a period of\nbusiness depression. The maladjust\nments with which the world now is\ncontending are very real and challenge\nthe best thought of the most highly\ntrained economic, business and finan\ncial minds In their solution.\nThe contrast is very sharp hrtween\nthe pace of business at the present\n.time and the hectic activity with which\nthe United States was cursed during\nfirst half of last year. The word\n\u2022\u2018cursed\u201d is used with emphasis in this\nconnection, as, in the last analysis,\nthere Is only one thing which brings\non business depression excluding\nnatural catastrophes and war\u2014and that\nIs some form of inflation. The way to\navoid depression Is to prevent Infla\ntion. The sure way to shun the morn\ning-after headache is to keep away\nfrom the party the night before.\nThe wild inflation and fevered ac\ntivity In which this country indulged\nlast year has thrown our perspective\nout of line, warped our judgment and\nunbalanced our sense of values. In\ncontrast with the pace of 1829. any\nthing like normal activity seems dull\nand uninteresting.\nPockets Bulging With Money.\nThe fact remains, however, that con\nditions in this country are not and\nnever have been as bad as we have\nbeen seeing them through our blue\ncolored spectacles since the collapse of\nthe stock market last Pall. The re\nmoval of the blue glass and stock ticker\nsymbols from one's vision enables one\nto see that the pockets of the Nation\nare so bulging with money that a thou\nsand-dollar bill Is glad to get to work\nat the rate of $lO a year; that the\nFederal Reserve Is in such herculean\nposition that Its reserves are close to\nthe record high of all time, and that\ndeposits in savings banks have estab\nlished new high records.\nTotal assets of the mutual savings\nbanks alone recently passed the ten\ntrillion mark for the tint time in his\ntory, their deposits of more than\n$9,000,000,000 \"representing the largest\naccumulation of small capital ever\nbrought together by one class of banks\nanywhere to the world,\u201d according to\nauthoritative statements. Mutual sav\nings hold about one-third of the\nsavings accounts in the banks of the\nUnited States. Such deposits do not\nrepresent manufactured credit, but\nactual savings which individuals In all\nwalks of life have pushed under the\ngrating at the receiving teller\u2019s window.\nA real problem has been created by\nthe volume of funds offered the savings\nbanks. Large deposits are being re\nfused and some institutions have for\nmulated rules preventing any one de\npositing over SI,OOO within a period of\nthree months. Numerous savings in\nstitutions in Greater New York have\nrecently reduced the rate of Interest\npaid on deposits.\nBaying Fewer Stored Up.\nDoes the spectacle of large deposits\nbeing refused at the tellers\u2019 windows\nand that of the banks being so put to\ntt to devise means to discourage de\nposits to volume indicate that the\nlfation Is poor, that the man on the\nstreet has no buying power? No\u2014from\nthe standpoint of the depositor, the\nsavings banks of the country represent\nmeat warehouses of stored up potential\nBuying power. Sooner or later, when\nthe unreascnlng fear which now grips\npeople is dispelled, this purchasing\npower will make Itself felt In filling up\nthe vacuum created to the period of\nunderconsumption through which the\ncountry now is passing.\nMeanwhile, the savings banks are\n\u25a0sing the vast deposits now being\nthrown at them for loans on real estate\nand to the purchase of rail, public util\nity and industrial bonds. This In itself\nis another evidence that we are in the\ntarty stages of returning normalcy.\nIf we will but remove the blue spec\ntacles from our eyes we will see the\ngreat corporations of our country with\ntremendous surpluses. At the top of the\nMg bull market these concerns were\nlanding nearly $4,000,000,000 In the call\nmoney market. Such loans now approx\nimate $500,000,000, the funds with\ndrawn now being used to more produc\ntive channels.\nV, with dear vision, we appraise the\npeesant position of these corporations.\nIt Is found that current earnings do\nnot present the gloomy picture visu\nalised by many on both Main Street\nand Wau Btreei Many companies now\nart enjoying larger earnings than last\nyear. Reports for the first six months\nof 1930, the latest period for which full\ncompilations are available, show more\nthan 100 corporations making larger\nprofits than In the first half of 1939.\nwhan general business activity was at\nfever beat. The surprising feature of\nthis compilation is that such a large\npercentage of the number reporting in\ncreased earnings are Industrial concerns.\nThis is the class usually the worst hit\nto periods of depression.\nISIS Earnings Increased.\nIncomplete compilations covering the\nfimt nine months of the year, while\nrevealing various companies showing\nincreases in earnings of worn tl per\ncent to more than 200 per cent over\nthe aorremonding period of 1929, do not\nmake as favorable a showing as In the\nfirst half of 1930. One hundred and\nEf&srsr &rz\u00a3J\u00a3\ntoJcfSFif o tt\"\ntiie corresponding months last year. In\ngiving proper weight to this figure, it\nmust be taken into consideration that\nit is comparing present earnings with\na period of intense activity and not\nwith normal business.\nConservative, efficient boards of direc\ntors. under ordinary conditions not con\nnected with speculation, do not vote to\ndistribute corporate profits to stockhold\ners unless their companies are prosper\nous. When there is so much talk about\ndepression, reduced operating schedules\nand vanishing profit margins, for a\nboard of directors to inauguarte divi\ndends on a stock to be almost\nbeyond the realm of possibility. But In\nthe eight months ended with August the\nnumber of initial dividends declared\nreached the astounding total of 433. In\nthe same time there also have been 177\nincreases in rates of disbursement.\nMute proof of a prosperity which we\nhave not been able to see through our\nindigo specs!\nStock dividends and \u201cextras\u201d are as\nsociated 1b our minds with capacity\noperations, expanding sales and soaring\nprofits. In fact, they have become so\nsynonymous with corporate prosperity\nthat by close students of the securities\nmarkets they are considered danger sig\nnals in bull markets. In the first eight\nmonths of 1930 there have been paid\n727 extra dividends, and stock dividends\nhave reached exactly the same total.\nBut the thick blue film on the glasses\nof the man in the street obscures this\nimpressive total of 1,454 extra and stock\ndividends.\nStock Dividends Increase.\nA comparison of these figures with\nthose for the corresponding period of\n1929 makes them even more surprising.\nIn the same eight months of last year\nextra and stock dividends totaled 1,463,\nor Just nine more than in the first eight\nmonths of this year. Either numerous\ncorporations must be prospering or many\ndirectors have parted from safe, con\nservative business policies. If there does\npot exist a corporate prosperity and\nsoundness of financial conditions not\nappreciated by the ipan on the street,\nindications are there will be many\nchanges In those who occupy directors\u2019\nchairs early in 1931.\nA compilation covering the first nine\nmonths of the year shows total cash\ndividend disbursements were more than\n$3,600,000,000,. an increase of about a\nhalf billion dollars over cash dividends\npaid In the same period last year.\nSounds strange, doesn\u2019t It, to hear this\nkind of news now, in a year of depres\nsion, when It is usually employed bv\npools at the top of the market as bull\nammunition for the purpose of pushing\nquotations higher?\nThere are other factors which seem\nstrangely out of place in a period of\nbusiness recession. One hears much of\nthe decline in exports of this country,\nand yet raw cottfen exports in September\nwere the heaviest for any September on\nrecord and showed an increase of more\nthan 24 per cent over the same month\nlast year. Wheat, including flour, ex\nported from principal ports of the United\nStates and Canada in the 17 weeks\nended with October 23 showed an in\ncrease of more than 41 per cent over the\ncorresponding weeks in 1929. This is in\nactual volume \u2014measured in bushels, not\nto dollars.\nMore Contagions Than Measles.\nThe epidemic of blue funk with\nwhich the country is now afflicted\nseems to be more contagious than the\nmeasles. Many statisticians seem to be\nbroken out with It and facts and fig\nures which are really optimistic when\ninterpreted correctly are served up\nwith wailing and gnashing of teeth. A\nrecent compilation showed that sales\nof 53 chain and mail-order concerns\nfor the first nine months of the year\nwere 1.1 per cent larger than In the\nsame period last year. Compared with\na normal growth of 3 per cent to 4\nper cent, this does not look so good.\nBut these sales were reported in dol\nlars. To get a correct view of this\npicture, the decline in commodity and\nretail prices must be taken into con\nsideration. Commodities, according to\none of the most reliable Indices, have\nregistered a decline of over 19 per cent\nduring the last year and are now down\nto 1915 levels. Retail prices are off\nfrom 9 to 30 per cent.\nIt is perfectly obvious that when\ncommodities are down nearly 20 per\ncent. It requires Just that much less\nmoney to buy the same quantity and\nkind of goods. Making allowance for\nthe decline in prices, the sales of the\nchain and mail-order companies were\nfar ahead of the same period last year\nin actual volume. The fact must not\nbe lost sight of that we don\u2019t eat or\nwear dollars, we Just measure by them,\nand that it is actual volume which\ncounts in such Indices, not dollar\nmeasurements.\nOne of the most important of the\nchain grocery companies now reports\nsales both ways, in dollars and actual\nvolume. In a recent period its sales\nwere 3.26 -per cent larger in dollars\nand more tiian 14 per cent larger in\ntonnage, than in the same period of\n1929. This is illustrative of how de\nceptive a business Index can be when\npresented In dollars without making\nallowance for the decline In commod\nity and retail prices. These factors\nmust be taken into consideration in in\nterpreting properly many of the busi\nness Indices presented in dollars, such\nas debits to Individual accounts, bank\nclearings, department store sales and\nall others which are related to goods\nand materials.\nWhile there is plenty of room for\nImprovement to business activity, when\nthe generally accepted Indices are cor\nrectly interpreted in the light of\nchanged conditions It is found that in\nmany lines the actual volume of goods\nchanging hands compares very favor\nably with normal and even with last\nyear in various Instances.\nLarge Tonnage By Track.\nIn freight car loadings, the figures\nwhich at the present time are making\nsuch a sorrowful showing and which\nhave caused some of the barometers of\nbusiness to fall below the 1921 level,\nthe large tonnage moved by truck\nmust be taken into account. Door to\ndoor movement of freight by truck\nseems to be Increasing with alarming\nrapidity from the standpoint of the\nrailroads, even for long-haul traffic.\nAt the present time there is no way of\nmeasuring this tonnage. If such an\nIndex were available it would serve to\nreduce very materially the falling off\nin freight movement shown* in car\nloadings.\nA brief resume of the present business\nrecession in contrast with the depression\nof 1920-21 reveals there is really no\ncomparison In Intensity, despite current\nstatements to the contrary. At that\ntime the Federal Reserve ratio was just\nabove 40. comparing with over 80 at the\npresent time: money was loaning at pro\nhibitive rates, with strong corporations\nfloating bond lssuas bearing 7 per cent\nand 8 per cent coupons, contrasting with\n4*4 per cent to B*4 per cent, and with\ntime money rates of 2 per cent to 3 per\ncent now; operations of the steel indus\ntry fell to 18 per cent of capacity,\nagainst the present rate of over 50 per\ncent; only a few corporations could show\nsurpluses in place of being In the posi\ntion to loan heavily in the call money\nmarket; one of the largest automobile\noonceras was cramped and trying to\nborrow $76,000,000 on Wall Street, and\nthen made the little banks over the!\ncountry finance the company; one of\nthe moat Important mail-order concerns\nwas saved from serious financial diffi\nculty by the president dumping In his\nprivate fortune; the unemployed were\nestimated at 8,000,000. comparing with\nthe 2.600,000 shown in the last census.\nThe bottom Mil out of commodity priosa;\nthe South American wharves were piled\nTHE SUNDAY STAB, WASHINGTON, D. C., NOVEMBER 16, 1930\u2014PART TWO.\nWhere Is America Going?\nJames J. Davis, Secretary of Labor, Declares Workers of Country Form Strong Foundation Stones\nBY J. F. CLASS.\nTHE workers of the country, Increasingly in\ntelligent and well informed, and conscious,\ntoo, of the dignity and independence of\nthe position accorded them to the schema\nof things, form a solid foundation upon\nwhich will be based the coming period of eco\nnomic and social advancement Which the ac\ncomplishments of the last quarter century Imply.\nThis is the underlying thought developed to\na conversation I have had with Secretary of\nLabor James J. Davis, which began with my\nquestion, \u201cWhat, Mr. Davis, do you consider the\ngreatest factor for confidence in our economic\nfuture?\"\nHe replied:\n\u201cThe country always will be safe as long as\nits management can be recruited from the rank\nand file.\u201d\nIndustry in the United States is doing that\nvery thing in fuller measure today than ever\nbefore, be pointed out; and\u2014a most significant\ncircumstance\u2014this leadership, which is bound\nto the rank and file by early ties of sympathy\nand understanding, remains responsive to its\nideals and needs.\n\u201cOther countries do not have the same situa\ntion,\u201d said Mr. Davis. \u201cIn some, of course, a\nconsiderable share of management comes freon\nthe ranks of the workers, but In others the masses\nof the people have not produced men quali\nfied for management. In America, with its vast\nnumbers of well informed, enterprising workers,\nthere is a continuous bubbllng-up of ambitious\ngenius. Manifesting Itself in a thousand dif\nferent ways, it assumes, among other functions,\nthat of management. Under its leadership we\nare constantly developing new avenues of prog\nress, finding ways to solve long-vexing problems.\nIntelligent Workers Needed.\n\u201cWe do not yet know the full benefits that will\nfollow from the processes by which our country\nhas given unlimited opportunity for education.\nWe do know that far from making the worker\nthe enemy of so-called capital, his wider knowl\nedge has enabled him to understand its neces\nsities, at tiie same time that it has equipped him\nto advance his own interests and attain full\nrecognition of his rights. From the reservoir of\nunderstanding created by his cultural oppor\ntunities, too, he provides new contributions to\nkiwwledge. We could not have the highly de\nveloped Industrial machinery of today without\nintelligent workers nor can we go on without\nthem tomorrow.\n\u201cOs course the latter Is not even a remote\ncontingency, for the worker, generally speaking,\nis thirsty for more knowledge. In answer to his\nrequirements, his fellows\u2014the workers in the\nresearch laboratories, the chemists, the engi\nneers, the Inventive geniuses, and educators them\nlelves\u2014make it easier and easier for him to ac\nquire education. If he cannot go to college he\ncan through reading, study, correspondence\ncourses and such agencies as the radio, educate\nhigh with refused merchandise, contracts\nwere tom up as scraps of paper and the\nensuing litigation lasted tor years. Com\npared with the difficulties encountered\nin 1920-21, the present depression seems\nmild in many ways.\nWhile the world-wide decline in com\nmodity prices has dime more to upset\nthings than any other single factor en\ntering Into the present maladjustments\nIn agriculture, commerce and industry,\nit Is not an unmixed evil. The drop to\nprices acts automatically to increase the\nsalaries of a very large proportion of the\npopulation of the United States, whose\nIncomes, when measured in dollars, re\nmain the same as last year. Real wages,\nas expressed to goods, have been greatly\nIncreased during the last year through\nthe enlarged purchasing power of the\ndollar.\nThe expenditure at this time of the\namount of these automatic increases to\nsalaries not only would prove very ad\nvantageous to the spenders, but soon\nwould usher to normal activity to busi\nness to this country. This buying power\nis now warehoused to the savings banks\nand has. but to be released through the\nelimination of fear and the restoration\nof confidence.\nTurkish Men Envy\nWomen Their Rights\nISTANBUL, Turkey.\u2014The Turkish\nwomen have traveled so far down the\nroad of freedom that the tables have\nturned and it is the man who shouts.\n\u201cI want equal rights with the women!\u201d\nNow that the Turkish women are work\ning, voting and dreaming of becoming\nDeputies they should be treated on an\nequal basis with the men, is the\nopinion of many in Istanbul. The trolley\ncompany has six seats strictly reserved\nfor women where no man may sit.\nThis is a \"Souvenir of the old days when\nwomen were veiled and had to sit be\nhind curtains and separate partitions.\nThat old law has been abolished, the\nwomen wear hats and show their faces\nto the world, and yet they still possess\nthe right to those separate seats.\nIf a man Is bold enough to sit to\none of these and there are women\nstanding, he is requested to get up by\nthe conductin\u2019. He \u2019might be loaded\ndown with packages, bent down with\nyears and white hair, but he must rise\nand give his place to a woman or a\nyoung girl and stand the rest of the\nway, bitterly grumbling against the\nwomen, the company and the world at\nlarge. It does not help to hide one\u2019s\nface behind a huge newspaper or pre\ntend to be deeply absorbed to street\nscenes. The women and the conductors\nare merciless.\nThe men of Istanbul are a little irri\ntated at this privilege of the women\nand they are thinking of uniting and\ndemanding that the women should not\nbe handled with gloves in this fashion.\nSince they shouted equality and yearned\nfor freedom, they should be allowed to\nstand to the trolleys and be stepped on\nJust like the men.\nMexico Pays Tribute\nTo Music in America\nIf a story to the Mexican newspaper\nEl Porvenir can be a criterion, then the\nUnited States is the world\u2019s most musi\ncal country. \u201cMusical activity,\u201d ac\ncording to this well informed Mexican\ndaily, \u201cIs rapidly making the American\na lover of music on a basis of true ar\ntistic culture. Foreigners who visit the\nUnited States are amazed at the flood\nof music that comes from every quarter,\neven the small town, of a country that\nIs currently reported to devote Itself ex\nclusively to the \u201cchase of the almighty\ndollar.\u201d In addition to professional or\nchestras, there are some 16,006 bands\ncomposed of children and young people\nwho attend the different schools and\nuniversities of the country. There is no\ncity, however small, that does not pride\nitself on Its student band, equipped with\nthe finest instruments, usually pur\nchased by popular subscription. Many\nof its units are composed of as many\nas 60 to 70 boys and girls.\"\nLeprosy Is Studied\nBy Hawaiian Group\nThe ancient scourge of leprosy is\nbeing intensively studied In Hawaii with\na view to steady reduction in the num\nber of cases and eventually to eradica- i\ntton. Gov. Lawrence M. Judd, who was\na Chicago visitor recently, has appoint\ned a committee which includes men who\nhave given many years of attention to\nleprosy cases. Their report, just con\ncluded but not made public, deals not\nonly with medical treatment, but with\n1 measures for segregstlan of- lepers and\ncloser control of the disease. Hawaii\n(or many years has treated leprosy with\nout special fear, knowing that care In\nhandling It sufficiently protects doctors\nand nurses from contamination. Mea\nsures suggested to the Governor by the\ncommission will be embodtgd In legisla\ntion by the territory ofuawaU next\nSorkm\nA\n;,v\njITH\nJAMES J. DAVIS.\nWHO HOLDS THE COUNTRY IS SAFE WITH\nLEADERSHIP RENEWED FROM THE RANK\nAND FILE.\n\u201cGranted that the radio spreads wide a great\ndeal that is useless, it still Is a tremendous in\nfluence lor good. For myself, I do not regard\nIt as a means of amusement, but as an agency\nfor Information and education. It affords me\nthe best in music, addresses, lectures, sermons.\nIn what college could the professors give me bet\nter lectures than I can hear over the radio?\n\u201cThe mental equipment of workers will grow.\nThey will contribute more and more to the en\nlightened management of industry\u2014and with to\nI IN LATIN AMERICA\nBy GASTON NERVAL.\nPOLITICAL PSYCHOLOGY.\nPSYCHOLOGY is indeed outstand\ning to the study of political\nscience. If we stop to.consider\nthe different ways in which dif\nferent people react to similar\nphenomena we would have the clue to\na far better understanding of political\nevents.\nWe may all have had common an\ncestors and similar beginnings; we may\nall have come from the same original\nbeing\u2014call him Adam or a monkey,\naccording to whether you believe with\nthe Bible or with the author of Dar\nwinism\u2014but the fact remains that after\na few thousand years the human mind\ntoday is divided into as many different\nways of thtoging as there are races on\nthe face of the earth.\nTime, history, geographic influences,\neconomic and social factors\u2014they have\nall contributed to create this marked\nvariation to psychological reactions\nwhich make it so difficult for the ma\njority of people to understand the atti\ntude and behavior of people of other\nlands.\nThe average American newspaper\nreader regards not only with surprise\nbut with a certain horror and disdain\nthe violent methods by which his Latin\nAmerican brother chooses to put\nthrough his political plans. He simply\ncannot understand why his Southern\nbrother should pursue the course of\npolitics with such passionate ardor, and\nwhy he should prefer the use of bullets\nto that of ballots to expressing his\npolitical dissatisfaction.\nFIND WAY OUT AT POLLS.\nIn the last five months he has read\nof four violent upheavals to South\nAmerican countries, caused primarily by\neconomic depression and an awakening\nof public sentiment against dictatorial\nforms of government. On the other\nhand, he has just seen a similar ten\ndency of public disapproval to his own\ncountry manifested to a far more demo\n-1 era tic way. Public discontent and bad\neconomic conditions resulted down on\nthe other side of the Rio Grande to\nfour major revolutions. The same ele\nments here have Just brought about an\nelectoral defeat of the party to power.\nThat is to say, the same popular reac\ntion which required the use of guns to\nLatin America found away out here\nthrough the polls.\nIt is true that to the former case\nan even greater issue was at stake, that\nof individual liberties, these having been\nrestricted by the governments recently\nousted from power. But even without\nthis the Latin American crises were\nbound to end to violent turmoil, Just\nas certainly as the I axon American\none was bound to be solved at the polls.\nMore temperamental, more passion\nate, with that ardent disposition typi\ncal of Latin blood seething constantly\nto his veins, the Latin American is\nmuch more emphatic than his North\nem neighbor to his political feelings.\nAnd being as yet little engaged to com\nmercial or industrial activities, he is\nalso more concerned to politics and\nmore dependent upon them.\nUnder these circumstances it la not\ndifficult to understand why any eco\nnomlc, social, religious or even intel\nlectual controversy must have a politi\ncal reaction among the Latin Amerl\ncans, and why this reaction has to\nbe a passionate and violent one.\nThe Latin Americans are less con\nservative, less tolerant, less patient, less\nlenient to politics. The prohibition laws,\nfor Instance, would have caused a revo-\nI lution to any Latin American country\nlong, long ago.\nAMERICAN EXPERTS.\nThose who still believe that one of\nthe veiled reasons behind the recent\nrevolutions In South America was a\nrebuke to the intervention of American\ncapital and of American experts whose\nservices had been engaged by the gov\nernments just overthrown will prob\nably be surprised to hear that the new\nPeruvian administration has asked\nProf. Edwin Kemmerer of Princeton\nUniversity to act as financial adviser\nin the reorganization of Peruvian na\ntional revenues and the stabilisation\nof Peruvian exchange.\nWhen the news of the downfall of\nthe Legula regime was first known here\na score a newspapers pointed out that\nthe deposed President' had been ex\ntremely friendly to American economic\npenetration in Peru and that the tri\numphant movement might be an ener\ngetic reaction against sueh a tendency.\nBusiness leaders became somewhat\nalarmed in this oountry, and the im\npression arose that the new Peruvian\nauthorities would be more reluctant in\nseeking the co-operation of American\nexperts.\nAs always happens with unpleasant\nnews, this misinterpretation amad\nrapidly \"\"\"\"t aagtatn d\u00dflst hmsmb*\nrn former high executive of this coun\ntry, to a syndicated article, listed that\nsupposedly anti-American sentiment as\none of the issues behind the Latin\nAmerican upheavals.\nAnd yet today that same adminis\ntration which was alleged to be fear\nful of American influence calls on one\nof the most outstanding American\neconomists to help to the financial re\nhabilitation of Peru.\nProf. Kemmerer, who is by no means\na stranger to Latin American condi\ntions, is at present acting to a similar\ncapacity to Colombia. He went there a\nfew months ago, engaged by President\nOlaya Herrera to make a close Investi\ngation of Colombian finances. He had\nbeen to Colombia once before, to 1923,\nand the recommendations he made at\nthat time had been responsible to a\nlarge extent for the re-establishment\nof Colombian finances to the last few\nyears. He had also been to other\nSouthern republics, to Chile, Ecuador,\nBolivia, Panama, etc., to all of which,\nwith the collaboration of several other\nAmerican experts, he had strengthened\nthe national financial systems, and\navoided the incurring of budget deficits,\nwhich had become almost traditional.\nWhen his present mission to Colom\nbia Is ended Prof. Kemmerer will prob\nably accept the Invitation of the Peru\nvian military government and lend his\nvaluable advice and vast economic ex\nperience for the task of readjusting\nfinancial conditions to Peru.\nIt is encouraging to see Latin Amer\nicans, to spite of ail the Ul-intentioned\ntalk of \u201cYankee imperialism,\u201d entrusting\nto American experts the solution of\ntheir financial problems. Confidence is\nthe basis of International good will.\nCAUGHT IN HIS OWN TBAP.\nPolitics plays queer tricks upon Latin\nAmerican politicians\u2014to fact, upon\npoliticians everywhere. But if politics\nare fickle znd contradictory all over the\nworld, as I said only a few days ago,\nthey art exceedingly so to Latin\nAmerica.\nIn this same column I had occasion\nto comment last week upon the change\nthat the latest Brazilian political events\nhad brought upon the fortunes of two\nmen prominent in them. While only a\nyear ago President Washington Luis\nwas opposing bitterly the candidacy of\nDr. Oetulio Vargas and denying him\nthe privilege of making his political\nspeeches to the public forums of the\nBrazilian capital, this month finds Dr.\nVargas entering Rio de Janeiro In tri\numph, amidst wild applause from the\npopulace and military forces, while the\nfate of the deposed President, Washing\nton Luis, held prisoner to Copacabana\nfortress, is to the hands of the new\nBrazilian leader.\nAnother incident, of which I read to\nthe cable reports, now adds an Ironical\ntouch to the situation. This cablegram\nfrom Rio de Janeiro states that the re\ncourse of \u201chabeas corpus\u201d invoked by\nthe distinguished prisoner of Copaca\nbana has been denied by the supreme\ncourt on the ground that the \u201cstate of\nsiege\u201d (martial law) decreed by Presi\ndent Luis himself before the triumph of\nthe revolution, suspended individual\nrights and allowed the taking of. ex\ntraordinary measures outside the provi\nsions of the constitution.\nThus Senhor Luis is caught to his\nown trap. The very same recourse he\nInvoked to temporarily dispose of his\nenemies and strengthen his own posi\ntion while in power prevents him now\nfrom obtaining his personal liberty. He\nhad ordered martial law as President\nof Brazil, and now hl\u00bb captors invoke\nthat same edict to keep him locked up.\nCertainly he did not know when he de\ncreed martial law\u2014which, so to speak,\n\u201clegalizes\u201d political imprisonment\u2014that\nhe was sanctioning his own captivity.\nIt might be said this time that Senhor\nWashington Luis has punished himself.\nCOLORED SPECTACLES.\nSome time ago, when Nicaragua was\nto the midst of a bloody civil war, and\nUncle Sam, urged by the Conservative\nadministration, had landed Marines on\nNicaraguan shores, American newspapers\nand American statesmen spoke of the\nrebellious Liberal faction to that coun\ntry as a \u201csmall minority of malcontents\u201d\nwho had no support at all among the\npeople of Nicaragua and no right to be\naccorded even the customary status of\nbelligerents.\nLater on. when a truce had been ar\nranged through the good offices of an\nAmerican envoy, and when, to accord\nance with It, free elections were held\nunder the supervision of American Ma\nrines, the Liberals proved to be to large\nmajority to the country and obtained\nlegally and peacefully the control of\ngovernment. In the fairest elections that\nNicaraguan history had known the Lib\nerals defeated that group of Conserve*\nlives which Unsq fiam had thought to\ndustry conceived as a form of social service to\nwhich the importance of their function, and the\nrelationship of industry to them, is fully recog\nnized.\n\u201cThe significance of a situation whereto the\nrelations of the parties to industry are governed\nby spiritual and moral premises to which angry\ndispute and violence are discounted is beyond\nImagination. In gaining such a position, the\nworkers have enhanced their prestige enormously.\nAnd of course they have added to this prestige\nby their participation to ownership, often to\nventures completely their own, and\u2014even mofb\nextensively\u2014management.\nSymptomatic of this condition of affairs Is\nthe fact that the time has passed when any con\ncern of importance can attach favored relatives\nof trig stockholders to the pay roll at the expense\nof the advancement of deserving workers; and\nthe fact that It is becoming Increasingly Infre\nquent for one corporation to go to another to\nrecruit men for highly paid executive positions.\n\u201cThe head of a great corporation employing\nperhaps 100,000 men told me that he would have\nliked very much to add to his executive staff a\nman of high ability connected with another cor\nporation. But he did not deem it wise so to do.\nThe morale of his organization would have been\ndestroyed, since the whole plan of promotion\nwould have been interrupted, and skilled men\nwho had worked for years to climb to certain\ngoals would have been disappointed and rendered\n\"Perquisites to Industry are becoming few and\nfar between. Conditions of competition demand\nthe greatest skill to management. Industry calls\nmore for leaden from its rank and file.\nSympathetic Management.\n\u201cThere Is another aspect, certainly as vital as\nany. The effect of leadenhip, thus constantly\nrenewed, Is to provide us with management never\nfar removed to sympathy from the rank and file.\nTo this we owe a great deal of the intelligent\nadjustment of human relationship to industry,\nwhich has counted so much to recent progress,\nand which must bear so heavily upon the trends\nof the future.\n\u201cBut how about those who do not desire lead\nership\u2014those who remain the rank and file? I\nasked.\n\u201cThey,\u201d said the secretary, \u201care the cautious\njudges of the men who lead the way, and from\nwhom they differ little execept to the matter of\naspirations. They desire to be faithful citizens,\nto have comfortable homes, to raise families of\nwhich they can be proud, to be good neighbors,\nand to share to community and other responsi\nbilities. They see more satisfaction to such a\nrole than to the most boundless rewards of ener\ngetic ambition.\n'They regard plans for progress judicially. If\nan Idea is good they accept it, for they want to\ngo forward. But their approach Is cautious.\nThey object to retreats, and so they attempt to\navoid mistakes.\u201d\n(Copyright. 1030.)\nbe the real representatives of the Nica\nraguan people.\nLast week American newspapers re\nported the results of this year\u2019s general\nelections In Nicaragua, which were also\nsupervised by American officials. Once\nagain the Liberal party, now In power,\nsweeps the country by a large margin of\nvotes. The followers of Oen. Moncada,\ntoday President of Nicaragua, yesterday\nleader of the Liberal revolt, win In ail\nthe important districts.\n(Copyright, 1930.>\nHuge World War Debts\nTo Take Center of Stage\n(Continued From First Page.)-\nother countries where Interest rates\nare low but the Interior situation ap\npears more secure, like Prance and the\nUnited States, have more gold t.han\nthey know what to do with.\nFrench banks, for example, had\n$250,000,000 Invested in Germany in\nshort term Joans, but since Adolf\nHitler\u2019s success In the elections, they\nhave withdrawn $150,000,000. Italy\nwould like a loan from Prance, but,\nthe political tension between the two\ncountries make It impossible.\nFrance, as already said, now holds\none-flfth and the United States two\nflfths of the world\u2019s monetary gold. In\nother words, some countries have too\nmuch, others far too little of the prec\nious metal for, the general good.\nThrough careful study of this credit\nsituation, it is felt, something may be\ndone to quiet the extremist element\nwho scare Investors away from certain\nneedy countries. If this proves to be\nthe case, the International Bank may\nyet earn In popular favor the name\n\u2018\u25a0Peace I Bank\u00b0\u2019^ o6ed f r namely the\nPUBLIC LIBRARY\nRecent accessions to the Public\nLibrary and lists of recommended read\nlng will appear In this column every\nSunday.\nFamous Men.\nBen F. Ferdinand Magellan.\nA-M274D.\nClark, E. B. William L. sibert. the\nArmy Engineer. E-Sl 12c.\nCraig, E. G. Henry Irving, E-Ir7D\u00dfc.\nLudwig, Emil. Three Titans. E-9L966tE.\nNlcolson, H. G. Portrait of a Diplomat\nist: Being the Life of Sir Arthur\nNicolson. E-C2157n.\nPot r V Stephen. D. H. Lawrence.\nE-L4354p.\nCare of Children.\nAmerican Academy of Political and\nSocial Science, Philadelphia. Post-\nWar Progress In Child Welfare.\nIGB3-Am3s.\nMac Dowell, Margaret. Simple Begin\nnings In the Training of Mentally\nDefective Children. 1921. IZF-M 14.\nTiotzkey, E. L. Institutional Cara and\nPlacing-Out. IG-T758.\nHome Economics.\nEllis. P. I. Americanization Through\nHome-Making. RY-E1 55.\nKauffman, T. E. Teaching Problems In\nHome Economics. RY-K 164 t.\nShultz, Mrs. Q. d\u201e and Schenk, Mrs.\nBeulah. The House That Runs It\nself. RY-Sh9s.\nSilverman, H. G., comp. Congratula\ntions. RZ-Sl3B.\nTravel.\nBorrow, George. Wild Wales. 1928\n(Everyman\u2019s Library.) G44-8647a.\nDavis, M. L. Uncle Sam\u2019s Attic: The\nIntimate Story of Alaska. G 945-\nD 29.\nHuddleston, Sisley, Between the River\nand the Hills. G39N-HB6b.\nMauclair, Camille. Florence. 1927.\nG3SF-M44.E.\nNewton, A. E. A Tourist in Spite of\nHimself. Gl2-N4B.\nPalmer. Frederick. Look to the East.\nG6O-P 18.\nAeronautics.\nClevenger, C. P. Modern Flight. 1928.\nSZ-Cs9Bm.\nGoldstrom, John. A Narrative History\nof Aviation. SZ-G57.\nGuggenheim, H. F. The Seven Skies.\nBZ-G93.\nKneen, O. H. Everyman\u2019s Book of\nFlying. BZ-K73.\nFiction.\nEiker, Mathilde. My Own Par Towers.\nFeucbtwanger, Lionel. Success.\nHamsun, KnuL Vagabonds.\nLehmann, Rosamond. A Note in Music.\nNorris, Kathleen. The Lucky Law\nrences.\nOstenso, Martha. The Waters Under\nthe Earth.\nWharton* Edith. Certain Beads,\nRUSSIANS PRACTICING\nSABOTAGE FOR TRADE\nWhile People Are Deprived of Necessi\nties at Home Country Sells Cheaply\nin Other Nations.\n(Continued From Third Page.)\nthe troubles of the civil war, and the\nFinns'were not unprepared to meet It.\nBut the prices the Soviet Is prepared to\naccept are definitely below Finnish\ncosts of production.\nA German merchant who formerly\nhandled only Finnish timber told mp\nthat he was obliged to transfer his\nbusiness to Russia or go bankrupt, so\nlarge are the cuts that are being made.\nMoreover, the Soviet is ever on\nthe lookout for fresh markets. Its\ngreat timber trust, Exportles, has\nrecently concluded an agreement\nwith a Lithuanian group, headed\nby a former premier, Galvanankas,\nwhich, I understand, will supply\nall the needs of that country. This Is\na nasty blow for Poland, destroying\nwhatever faint hopes the Poles may\nhave had of exporting their timber to\nMemal.\nAt the head of the state trusts in\nRussia are shrewd men, well Informed\nabout market tendencies. Observing\nthe growing demand for ply-wood, Ex\nportles is selling good quality wood of\nthis description at prices ranging from\n$3 to $5 a ton below market levels.\nIt Is not generally realized that It\nhas lately been the policy of the Soviet\ntrusts to cut in on markets which they\nknow perfectly well they cannot con\ntinue to supply. Thus, within the last\nfew months, Russia decided to enter\nthe sausage casings market and slashed\nprices with such effect that American\nbeef middles which had been selling at\n$11.25 per set fell to 60 cents. Suddenly\nthe Russian supplies dwindled to an al\nmost Insignificant volume, but still\nenough to keep prices well below their\nformer levels.\nPurposes of Russia.\nFrom this It may be argued that\nRussia\u2019s motive in slaughtering prices Is\nnot merely to get dollars, and to get\nthem quickly, but that there la the in\ntention of deliberately sabotaging West\nern Industry.\nSimilarly with fruit. Russia to not at\npresent a great fruit-exporting country,\nyet by dint of cutting prices to a figure\nwell below that at which American and\nAustralian producers are abla to supply,\nso a prominent German Importer In\nformed mo, Russia has doubled her ex\nports of apples to Germany within the\nlast 12 months. They now total\n7,000,000 tons.\nA trade agreement with Italy, signed\nIn August, Is in full swing. In return\nfor Italian manufactures, chiefly air\nplanes, engines and motor cars, valued\nat $10,000,000 annually, Russia to sup\nplying Italy with naphtha, grain and oil.\nSpecial clauses give Italian ships privi\nleges In the Black Bea, enabling Russian\ngrain to be shipped to Genoa m Italian\nbottoms.\nAlready 2,500,000 quintals, or one\nsixth of Italy's annual consumption, has\nbeen obtained from Russia, and the\nquantity to to be increased each month.\nIt Is being sold at prices well below\nthose of the native product. Italians\nare asking whether their farmers are to\nbe sacrificed to the Russian dumpers.\nVast Wheat Harvest.\nThe dumping of wheat to Indeed the\nmost serious and spectacular aspect of\nRussia\u2019s novel campaign. The year\u2019s\nbumper harvest, estimated at 90,000,000\ntons, exceeds the normal needs of the\npopulation by at least 10,000,000 tons.\nIn forming any estimate of the probable\nextent of the Boviet grain exports It\nmust be remembered that bread to a\nrationed commodity and that the nor\nmal needs of the people are not likely\nto be supplied. On the other hand,\nthere Is much wastage through lack of\nstorage and transport facilities and the\ndifficulty of collection. The Soviet au\nthorities place the limit of export at\n5,000,000 tons, of which about half will\nbe wheat, and this figure 1$ not likely to\nbe greatly exceeded.\nBut 5,000,000 tons of grain thrown on\nan already glutted market can play\nhavoc with prices. In Britain, where\nof all the grain coming from overseas\n60 per cent has been Russian, the situa\ntion has led to fierce criticism of the\npropriety of the action of the Co-opera\ntive Wholesale Society, the largest flour\nmilling organization in the country, in\nimporting nearly as much Russian grain\nas It bought from Canada, where a large\nsurplus has been held over from lsst\nFrance Holds Favorable Position\nOver Italy in Unsettled Europe\n(Continued From Flwt Page.)\ntrlalists have tried in the last two yean\nto solve this last problem by the crea\ntion of a certain number of cartels, and\nfor a while it looked as if they would\nbe able to bring about better political\nfeelings between the two countries.\nLately, however, certain political Influ\nences- have retarded the work of these\nIndustrialists, and today It seems that\ntheir endeavon are to be doomed to\nfailure.\nPolitical Problems Blamed\nConsequently many American stu\ndents of the European situation are\ninclined to believe that the solution of\nthe political problems would bring\nabout a relaxation of the existing ten\nsion and things would Improve m the\neconomic field as soon as the political\ntroubles were settled. This view is\nshared by many responsible United\nStates officials. They maintain, how\never, that it is a poor plan to settle\na dispute while the leading antagonists\npack guns and keep the finger on the\ntrigger. The more nervous one might\nfire unexpectedly and nobody then\nwould be able to mediate a reconcilia\ntion until one party was defeated. For\nthis reason the President of the United\nStates is very anxious that the Euro\npean nations should agree to summon\nas soon as possible a general disarma\nment conference. If France and Italy\nwould agree to come to that confer\nence in a less bellicose spirit than they\nare today much could be achieved, u\nthe European nations would agree to be\nreasonable and disarm, the United\nStates might be able to do a good deal\ntoward the solution of their economic\nills. Nobody in this country can pos\nsibly listen to the question of readjust\nment of the reparation and debt ques\ntion as long as hundreds of millions of\ndollars are wasted on arms and am\nmunitions.\nThe French prime minister, Andre\nTardleu, has explained France's posi\ntion in a speech made at Alenoon, France,\non the 28th of September. He stated\nthat France was willing to co-operate\nwith the rest of the world for the\norganization of peace on the triple\nbasis of security, arbitration and dis\narmament. But she refuses to invert\nthe order of these three conditions.\nWhat the French prime minister meant\nwas that France will not agree to dis\narm unless Great Britain is willing to\ngive her a Mediterranean pact and\nunless the United States decided to\ngive the European nations the assur\nance that she would be ready to con\nsult and arbitrate in case of trouble in\nEurope.\nThis had been told openly by both\nMonsieur Tardleu and Monsieur Brland\nto our delegates during the London\nNaval Conference. It is unlikely that\nthis point of view of the French prime\nminister would tag even considered by\nthe administration, fmarto believes\nin peace add friendship among na\ntions. She is most anxious tmt the\nEuropean nations should comel|p an\nunderstanding with each other, but her\nideas of achieving this are dlffMst\nf We Mat\nseason, and more than five times as\nmuch as It purchased from Australia.\nThe society replied that It merely\nfollowed other buyers, who were guided\nby the ordinary business consideration\nof purchasing In the cheapest market.\nIt to, however, argued with some force\nthat the ordinary laws of political\neconomy do not here apply. The nine\nteenth century economists, who hymned\nso rapturously the glories of free com\npetition, never envisaged dumping on\nso grpid a scale by a foreign govsrn\n*ment In absolute oontrol of the re\nsources and labor of a vast country, a\ngovernment whose avowed policy to to\nbring about a world revolution. Ex\ntraordinary situations, It Is argued, need\nextraordinary remedies.\nThose who advocate that British\nwheat purchases should be organised\non a quota basis, which would greatly\nreduce purchases from the United\nStates, have found that Russian dump\nlng has greatly strengthened their case,\ni An agreement between Britain and the\nDominions, whereby the latter will sup\nply 55 per cent of the mother coun\ntry's wheat requirements, has been con\ncluded by the delegates to the Imperial\nConference.\nFrance, first country officially to sub\nject Importation of grain from Russia\nto a system of licenses, is moved rather\nby fear of what may happen than by\nany present dislocation of the French\nmarket. Soviet Imports into France\nare relatively small. The French Gov\nernment, however, was forced at the\nbeginning of the year to take action\nto maintain grain prices in the in\nterest of the farmer, the strongest po\nlitical force in France, and Is naturally\nanxious that Soviet Imports shall not\ndislocate Its machinery.\nOfficial circles in Moscow refuse to\nbelieve that the French restrictions ere\nInspired by anything but political mo\ni lives. Similarly, the outcry against\ndumping In the United States to re\ngarded as an attempt by the Republi\ncans to dlsttact attention from the\npresent business depression and to win\nover the support of the American\nfarmer by saving the country from the\nold bogey of the \"red terror.\u201d\nLooks to Industrialisation.\nIn a recent editorial Izvestla admits\nthat the Soviet desires to get ready\nmoney to carry on Its program of In\ndustrialisation, but denies that It to\nasking anything but a fair price far its\ngoods.\n\"Unlike capitklists, we do not wish to\nachieve our aim at the expense of the\nconsuming masses abroad,\u201d says the\nwriter voicing the view of the Kremlin.\n\"For that reason we refused the offs*\nof Kreuger, the match king; Deterdlng,\nthe British oil magnate, and other cap*-\nttallst groups when they offered us fa\nvorable conditions for the purchase of\nmatches or for oil production to enforce\ntheir own monopoly and raise prices\nthrough the world.\n\"Because we declined these greedy\nplans for gain, the Kreugers and D*-\nterdings have begun a new campaign\nagainst us and try to confuse the peas\nant masses abroad by throwing the\nblame for the current world dspremlon\nupon the Soviet.\u201d\nSo speaks the Soviet, using arguments\nIt hopes are already familiar In the\ncities of America and Western Eu\nrope, where the \u201cunlnstructed manses\u201d\nmay well wonder whether the fact that\nthe Soviet can sell Its produce at such\nlow prices Is not conclusive evidence\nthat they have been the victims es\ncapitalist exploitation.\nIn my opinion, the rulers of Huerta\nare seeking to kill two birds with on*\nstone. Primarily Russia wants dollars\nImmediate and at all costs for Iter gl\nritic plans of Industrialisation, and if\nobtaining them she Is able to dis\ncredit the capitalist system, so much\nthe better.\nBut propaganda to a by-product, not\n1 the Immediate aim. Meanwhile the\nRussian people tighten their belts and\nsnatch what comfort they can from the\nred banners forecasting the achleve\nments of the coming year which hang\n1 from every public building, store, fae\ntory and place of entertainment.\n1 Are they content with promises and\nhopes? The five-year plan has reached\na critical stage. What of the future?\n1 These are questions my next artiest\ntomorrow, seeks to answer.\n1 (Copyright, 1930. br North American New*.\npaper Alliance.)\nlleve that antagonistic parties nhonffl\nmeet in a room after they have parked\ni their guns outside.\nBut even before one could think es\nconvening a general disarmament con\nference it is thought necessary that\nItaly and France should agree to solve\ntheir naval problem. After the London\nNavi Conference it was understood\nthat Italy and France would continue\nto discuss their problems quietly and\nwithout much publicity. They have\ndone so, but the results have been\nnegattve. The Italians suggested to\nthe French the following agreement:\nFrance and Italy should have, respec\ntively, by 1886 a global tonnage of\nlarge and small cruisers, destroyers and\nsubmarines of 630,000 and 530,000 tons\neach. That is to say that the differ\nence between the two navies should bo\n100,000 tons, while today Ranee has\n200,000 tons more than Italy. (3) no\nnumber of naval units and the maxi\nmum global tonnage of each category\nto be built between now and 1836\nshould be fixed now and neither nation\nshould be entitled to build more than\nprovided in the agreement. (3) There\nshould be no further building of sub\nmarines beyond what had been decided\nin this year\u2019s naval program. That\nwould give France 77,000 tone of sub\nmarines. while Italy would have only\n52.000 tons.\nThe French rejected these proposals\nbecause they maintain that they were\ntoo much In Italy\u2019s favor. Franco, say\nthe French naval experts, has a large\nnumber of obsolescent cruisers, while\nItaly\u2019s cruisers are all practically new.\nFurthermore the French submarine\nprogram calls for 87,000 tons by 1836,\nwhile under the Italian scheme France\n\u2022should have by that time only 72,000\ntons.\nFrance Helds Oat\nThe conversations between the two\ncountries have been indefinitely post\nponed, but it is not unlikely that they\nmay be resumed before long. American\nand British diplomats at Paris and\nRome are doing their utmost to con\nvince Italy and Ranee of the necessity\nof settling their naval argument as\nsoon as possible. Whether they will be\nsuccessful is difficult to say at the\npresent moment, but it appears that\nthe Italians seem to be responsive to\nour suggestions. If Ranee can be con\nvinced that it is to her own interest\nas well as to tile interest of the world\nto reach an agreement with Italy be\nfore the end of the year, it la behoved\nin well Informed quarters in Washing\nton that the general disarmament con\nference could be summoned seme time\nnext year with a fair chance of suceesa.\nThe American Government is deter\nmined to participate in that conference\nin a very friendly spirit but R will\nmake it clear to all concerned that it\nwill discuss nothing but the questions\nrelating to general disarmament. Once\nthe nations of the world have agreed to\na policy of reasonable disarmament and\nhave signed a treaty to that effect all\nother questions which are now disturb\ning Europe, such as arbitration, con\nfeSSSSSS","height":"25257","width":"19659"}}
